WHY DO SHIAS DO “MAATAM”? Maatam means to lament and is the most misrepresented part of Azadari thanks to the overtly “bloody” imagery that one comes across when one Googles this.
.
It is NOT obligatory to perform Maatam with chains, knives and swords that sends streams of blood down your clothes. This is a matter of someone’s personal choice and faith and for this reason, our scholars do not discourage or encourage it.
.
Maatam can simply be beating your chest with your bare hands to the sounds of a Nauha (a tragic poem recounting the events of Karbala, sometimes from the perspective of Imam Hussain or his family or the inner thoughts of those who live today expressing grief towards the Imam). 
.
This is NOT something the Shias have invented. Maatam has been the practice of our Imams, starting from the fourth Imam Zainul Abideen, the son of Imam Hussain, who succeeded him.
.
It is a way of expressing grief and extreme anguish to the passing of someone close and personal. Each Shia reveres the Imam and his family as individuals deeply personal to them and hence, perform Maatam to pay their respects.
.
.
.
.
